JavaScript promises are wicked cool. Wicked. Cool. Like POGs in the mid-90's cool. Like cats on roombas cool. Like dogs doing sick skateboard tricks cool. Like gleaming the cube Christian Slater cool.

<img class=" size-full wp-image-912 aligncenter" src="https://jaredbarbozablog.files.wordpress.com/2017/10/37ae108f029abb0b569811da2b57cf9f.jpg" alt="37ae108f029abb0b569811da2b57cf9f" width="398" height="599" />

They are that cool.

Trust me.

But in case you don't believe me yet - I'm honestly not sure how you couldn't have been convinced already, but hey, I'm not here to judge, I'm here to talk about how cool promises are.

I guess I could start off by saying that the main reason promises are wicked cool is that they let you execute functions asynchronously in javascript, but this isn't exactly a new concept to javascript. The DOM and jQuery used an event-driven pub/sub model back before it was cool. And then AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) became the hottest buzz in tech (hotter than "unidirectional data flow" or "higher order component"). Then node came along with it's async-first I/O model. But as far as control flow was concerned, things remained roughly the same as they were in the early 2000's.

And this is why promises are wicked cool.

What I'm talking about is callbacks. Callbacks are essential to javascript. You can't do anything without them.
<pre>var fs = require('fs');
fs.readFile('/full/path/to/file.txt', function(err, data) {
  if (err) throw err;
 doSomething(data.toString());
});</pre>
<p style="text-align:center;"><em>even reading a file is impossible without callbacks</em></p>
So how do promises - those awesome pog slammers of code - help with callbacks? Well let's rework that earlier code to use promises.
<pre>var fs = require('fs');
<strong>function loadFile(filePath) {</strong>
<strong>  return new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {</strong>
    fs.readFile(filePath, function(err, data) {
      if (err) return reject(err);
      resolve(data.toString());
    });
<strong>  });</strong>
<strong>}</strong>

loadFile('/full/path/to/file.txt').then(doSomething);</pre>
Adding a few new lines of code (shown in bold because I am a expert blogger) let's the code take advantage of promises to wrap the callback-based code. The code still runs asynchronously and we have a much nicer API to use when reading our file.

Promises take a single function as their only argument. This function is going to be the actual task the promise is going to perform, and it is executed immediately when the promise is created.

This task function is passed two functions as arguments. These functions are used by your task code to signal the promise processor when your task has completed. the first is called when your task completes successfully - typically we name this argument <strong>resolve.</strong>The second argument should be called if your task fails for any reason - typically this argument is named<strong>reject</strong>.

So in the example above you can see that if <strong>fs.readFile</strong> encounters an error, we call <strong>reject </strong>with the error and if everything is cool we call <strong>resolve</strong> with the file contents.

This is a good start but promises really shine when you use them as part of a workflow. Let's add a feature to remove any passwords from our file after we read it in. First, we'll start with the old callback code.
<pre>var fs = require('fs');
<strong>function sanitizeContents(contents, callback) {</strong>
<strong>  contents = contents.replace(/passwords/ig, '');</strong>
<strong>  callback(contents);</strong>
<strong>}</strong>

fs.readFile('/full/path/to/file.txt', function(err, data) {
  if (err) throw err;
<strong>  sanitizeContents(data.toString(), function(sanitaryContents) {</strong>
    doSomething(sanitaryContents);
<strong>  });</strong>
});</pre>
This doesn't look bad at all. But what if we wanted to do more work to the file before handing it over to our doSomething function? Then we're going to need to nest more operations in our callbacks.
<pre>fs.readFile('/full/path/to/file.txt', function(err, data) {
  if (err) throw err;
<strong>  sanitizeContents(data.toString(), function(sanitaryContents) {</strong>
<strong>    translateContents(sanitaryContents, 'es-es', function(i18nTxt) {</strong>
<strong>      writeTranslationToDb(i18nTxt, dbname, function(result) {</strong>
<strong>        logResult(result, function(logResult) {</strong>
<strong>          // its just callbacks, all the way down</strong></pre>
<p style="text-align:center;"><em>if you stare long enough at the abyss, the abyss calls your callback function</em></p>
That's a super contrived and exaggerated example, but it makes my point. Data flow is very tightly coupled to that area of code where the file gets read and that's going to be a pain in the butt when that needs to change.

Let's assume we updated each of the methods above to support promises instead of using callbacks, or maybe we even craft a wrapper function like loadFile. How does that change the data flow of our application?
<pre>loadFile('/full/path/to/file.txt')
  .then(sanitizeContents)
  .then(translateContents)
  .then(writeTranslationToDb)
  .then(logResult);</pre>
This looks a lot better, our process is no longer nested inside multiple callbacks and we can more easily update the process, just by changing the order of the steps. This, to me is what makes promises super useful especially when I'm building out a script that has to process data through several steps.

